        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">University “Pitt” Club</hi></placeName>
                    <salute>My dear Father</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am sorry to say that I have only <hi rend="superscript">£</hi>46–5<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>– in the bank, &amp; the two bills of Burn’s are together £115<ref target="#foot.f2"/>   I am afraid I must have been shockingly extravagant some how; &amp; very idle not kept accounts so that I could seen how things were going. I only got my pass book this morning or I would have written to you before</p>
<p>Your affec son | Francis Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7346.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Francis Darwin, 18 October [1870]</ref> (<hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 18).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_742.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Robert Burn</ref> was Francis’s tutor at Trinity College, Cambridge, where Francis was an undergraduate from 1866 until 1870, when he received his BA (<hi rend="italic">Admissions to Trinity College, Cambridge</hi> 5: 329,<hi rend="italic"> Cambridge University calendar</hi> 1870, p. xxiv; see also <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 13, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4945.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Robert Burn, 2 December [1865]</ref>). CD recorded a payment to Francis of £115 on 18 October 1870 in his Account books–cash account (Down House MS).</note>
        </div>        
            
